<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-842-362  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 842 362.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Sept 1990 v19 n11 p121(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sprint takes a tumble but top man says 'all's well.' (interviewwith US Sprint Communication Pres Ronald LeMay) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mulqueen, John T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The president of US Sprint Communications Co., Ronald LeMay, saysalthough Sprint has been through some tough times, he has highconfidence in the business and no regrets of taking on the job aspresident.andP;  Sprint plans to reinvest in resources for new growth,which means eliminating about 1,000 jobs.andP;  A new advertisingcampaign is also planned with revision of plans for the massmarket.andP;  There will be a new focus on data communications.andP;  LeMayfeels that the market is big enough for ATandamp;T, MCI and Sprint butif the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) allows ATandamp;T toexercise its power it can adversely affect its competitors.andO;Sprint is also asking the FCC to take steps in revising lineleasing regulations for the international market where ATandamp;T hasmuch of the share.andP;  LeMay does not believe that regional Belloperating companies will get into the long-distance market in thenear future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   US Sprint Communications Co. (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     Telephone companiesMarketing StrategyManagementFinancial StabilityCompetition.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Ronald LeMay. (portrait)Person:    LeMay, Ronald (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>